results.name: Position of the first n-digit prime occurring in the decimal expansion of e.
link: Harvey P. Dale, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..200
example: a(1) = 1 because the initial digit "2" of e is prime.
mathematica: With[{ed = RealDigits[E, 10, 10000][[1]]}, Table[Position[Partition[ed, n, 1], _?(PrimeQ[FromDigits[#]] && #[[1]] != 0 &), {1}, 1, Heads -> False], {n, 100}]] // Flatten
results.author: _Harvey P. Dale_, Apr 25 2016
